 animus but in the overempowerment of men and the overentitlement of society to women's unpaid labor and undervalued contributions. This is a book about misogyny without misogynists. From antidiscrimination law to abortion bans, the law fails women by keeping society's dependence on women's sacrifices invisible. Via a tour of constitutional change around the world, After Misogyny shows how to remake constitutional democracy. Women across the globe are going beyond the antidiscrimination paradigm of American legal feminism and fundamentally resetting baseline norms and entitlements. That process, what Suk calls a ";constitutionalism of care,"; builds the public infrastructure that women's reproductive work has long made possible for free.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.xSocial aspects 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.xSocial aspects. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh  aconstitutional litigation.  ademocratic constitutionalism.  afeminist lawmaking.  agender equality in legal system.  alaws of patriarchy.  ame too.  amisogynistic culture.  areproductive justice.  asexual violence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520381964?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520381964423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520381964/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY